We prove that the norm of the linear functional `b ‚Ü¶ ‚ü®x, b y‚ü©_‚Ąā` is bounded by `‚ÄĖx‚ÄĖ * ‚ÄĖy‚ÄĖ`. This follows from `norm_inner_le_norm` and the fact that `‚ÄĖb y‚ÄĖ ‚Č§ ‚ÄĖb‚ÄĖ * ‚ÄĖy‚ÄĖ`.

```tactics
/-- Let `a` a normal bounded operator. By the continuous functional calculus, there is an injective
homomorphism from `C((spectrum ‚Ąā a), ‚Ąā)` to  `H ‚ÜíL[‚Ąā] H`, informally denoted by `f => f(a)`. This
definition just makes it a continuous linear map.
cf. Rudin "Functional Analysis" Theorem 11.18, the proof of Theorem 12.23, first paragraph.
-/
def cfcCLM : C((spectrum ‚Ąā a), ‚Ąā) ‚ÜíL[‚Ąā] H ‚ÜíL[‚Ąā] H
    := ((cfcHom ha.isStarNormal : C((spectrum ‚Ąā a), ‚Ąā) ‚Üí‚čÜ‚āź H ‚ÜíL[‚Ąā] H).toLinearMap).mkContinuous 1
        ( by simp only [AlgHom.toLinearMap_apply, StarAlgHom.coe_toAlgHom, one_mul];
              exact fun f => le_of_eq (norm_cfcHom a f))
```

This defines `cfcCLM` as the continuous linear map corresponding to the continuous algebra homomorphism `cfcHom` restricted to the C*-algebra of continuous functions on the spectrum of `a`. The `mkContinuous` is creating a continuous linear map from the algebra homomorphism.

```tactics
/-- The same map `f => f(a)` as a continuous algebra homomorphism.
-/
def cfcCAH : C((spectrum ‚Ąā a), ‚Ąā) ‚ÜíA[‚Ąā] H ‚ÜíL[‚Ąā] H
    := ContinuousAlgHom.mk (cfcHom ha.isStarNormal : C((spectrum ‚Ąā a), ‚Ąā) ‚Üí‚čÜ‚āź H ‚ÜíL[‚Ąā] H).toAlgHom
        (by apply @continuous_of_linear_of_bound _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ _ (cfcHom ha.isStarNormal).toAlgHom.map_add'
              (cfcHom ha.isStarNormal).toLinearMap.map_smul' 1
            simp only [AlgHom.toRingHom_eq_coe, RingHom.toMonoidHom_eq_coe,
              AlgHom.toRingHom_toMonoidHom, OneHom.toFun_eq_coe, MonoidHom.toOneHom_coe,
              MonoidHom.coe_coe, StarAlgHom.coe_toAlgHom, one_mul]
            exact fun f => le_of_eq (norm_cfcHom a f))
```

Similarly, `cfcCAH` is the continuous algebra homomorphism corresponding to `cfcHom`.

```tactics
@[simp]
lemma cfcCLM_apply (f : C((spectrum ‚Ąā a), ‚Ąā)) : cfcCLM ha f = cfcHom ha.isStarNormal f := rfl
```

This lemma simplifies the application of `cfcCLM`.

```tactics
/-- The composition of the linear functional and the continuous functional,
`f => ‚ü™x, f(a) y‚üę_‚Ąā` as a continuous linear functional. -/
def cfc_toLinearFunctional (x y : H) : C((spectrum ‚Ąā a), ‚Ąā) ‚ÜíL[‚Ąā] ‚Ąā
    := compSL C(spectrum ‚Ąā a, ‚Ąā) _ _ _ _ (toLinearFunctional x y) (cfcCLM ha)
```

This defines `cfc_toLinearFunctional x y` as the composition of `toLinearFunctional x y` and `cfcCLM ha`. This is a continuous linear functional on `C((spectrum ‚Ąā a), ‚Ąā)`.

```tactics
@[simp]
lemma cfc_toLinearFunctional_apply (f : C((spectrum ‚Ąā a), ‚Ąā)) (x y : H) :
    cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y f = ‚ü™x, (cfcHom ha.isStarNormal f y)‚üę_‚Ąā := rfl
```

This lemma simplifies the application of `cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y`.

```tactics
/-- For each pair `x y : H`, the linear map `f => ‚ü™x, f(a) y‚üę_‚Ąā`has norm `‚ÄĖx‚ÄĖ * ‚ÄĖy‚ÄĖ`.
This follows from the bound `toLinearFunctional_bounded` and the fact that
`f => f(a)` is an isometry, `norm_cfcHom`. -/
lemma cfc_toLinearFunctional_bound (x y : H) : ‚ÄĖcfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y‚ÄĖ ‚Č§ ‚ÄĖx‚ÄĖ * ‚ÄĖy‚ÄĖ := by
  apply ContinuousLinearMap.opNorm_le_bound
  ¬∑ positivity
  ¬∑ intro f
    simp only [cfc_toLinearFunctional_apply]
    calc
      ‚ÄĖ‚ü™x, ((cfcHom (IsSelfAdjoint.isStarNormal ha)) f) y‚üę_‚Ąā‚ÄĖ
        ‚Č§ ‚ÄĖx‚ÄĖ * ‚ÄĖ((cfcHom (IsSelfAdjoint.isStarNormal ha)) f) y‚ÄĖ := norm_inner_le_norm x
          (((cfcHom (IsSelfAdjoint.isStarNormal ha)) f) y)
      _ ‚Č§ ‚ÄĖx‚ÄĖ * (‚ÄĖ((cfcHom (IsSelfAdjoint.isStarNormal ha)) f)‚ÄĖ * ‚ÄĖy‚ÄĖ) :=
        mul_le_mul_of_nonneg_left (le_opNorm ((cfcHom (IsSelfAdjoint.isStarNormal ha)) f) y)
          (norm_nonneg x)
      _ = ‚ÄĖx‚ÄĖ * ‚ÄĖy‚ÄĖ * ‚ÄĖ((cfcHom (IsSelfAdjoint.isStarNormal ha)) f)‚ÄĖ := by ring
      _ = ‚ÄĖx‚ÄĖ * ‚ÄĖy‚ÄĖ * ‚ÄĖf‚ÄĖ := by rw [norm_cfcHom a f]
```

We prove that the norm of `cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y` is bounded by `‚ÄĖx‚ÄĖ * ‚ÄĖy‚ÄĖ`. This follows from `norm_inner_le_norm` and the fact that `‚ÄĖcfcHom ... f y‚ÄĖ ‚Č§ ‚ÄĖcfcHom ... f‚ÄĖ * ‚ÄĖy‚ÄĖ`, and `‚ÄĖcfcHom ... f‚ÄĖ = ‚ÄĖf‚ÄĖ` by `norm_cfcHom`.

```tactics
/-- For each pair `x y : H`, one obtains a complex measure `E_{a, x ,y}` from the continuous linear
functional `f => ‚ü™x, f(a) y‚üę_‚Ąā` by the Riesz-Markov-Kakutani theorem.
cf. Rudin "Real and complex analysis" Theorem 6.19 (2), combined with the bound by
`cfc_toLinearFunctional_bound`.-/
def cfc_toComplexMeasure (x y : H) := ComplexRMK.rieszMeasure (compSL C‚āÄ((spectrum ‚Ąā a), ‚Ąā)
  C((spectrum ‚Ąā a), ‚Ąā) ‚Ąā _ _ (cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y)
  (@ZeroAtInftyContinuousMap.ContinuousMap.liftZeroAtInftyCLE
  (spectrum ‚Ąā a) ‚Ąā ‚Ąā _ _ _ _ _ _).symm.toContinuousLinearMap)
```

This defines `cfc_toComplexMeasure x y` as the complex measure obtained from `cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y` via the Riesz-Markov-Kakutani theorem. The `compSL` is converting the linear functional to a continuous linear map on the space of continuous functions.

```tactics
/-- The integral of a Borel function `f` against `E_{a, x,y}` is bounded by `‚ÄĖx‚ÄĖ * ‚ÄĖy‚ÄĖ`.
We should have an analogue of `MeasureTheory.lintegral_le_const` for `ComplexMeasure.integral`.
-/
lemma bfc_bounded (x y : H) {C : ‚ĄĚ} {f : (spectrum ‚Ąā a) ‚Üí ‚Ąā}  (hf_bounded : ‚ąÄ x, ‚ÄĖf x‚ÄĖ ‚Č§ C)
    (hX : @Measurable _ _ (borel (spectrum ‚Ąā a)) _ f) :
    ‚ÄĖ(cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y).integral f‚ÄĖ ‚Č§ ‚ÄĖx‚ÄĖ * ‚ÄĖy‚ÄĖ * C := by
  sorry
```

This lemma states that the integral of a bounded Borel function `f` with respect to `cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y` is bounded by `‚ÄĖx‚ÄĖ * ‚ÄĖy‚ÄĖ * C`, where `C` is the bound on `‚ÄĖf x‚ÄĖ`. The proof is missing.

```tactics
/-- The linear functional from bounded Borel functions `f` to `‚ąę f z ‚ąāE_{a, x ,y} z` as a bounded
linear functional (bounded by `‚ÄĖx‚ÄĖ * ‚ÄĖy‚ÄĖ`). All the remaining properties should follow from
the definition and `bfc_bounded`. -/
def toBoundedBilin {C : ‚ĄĚ} (f : (spectrum ‚Ąā a) ‚Üí ‚Ąā)
  --(hf_bounded : ‚ąÄ x, ‚ÄĖf x‚ÄĖ ‚Č§ C) (hf_measurable : @Measurable _ _ (borel (spectrum ‚Ąā a)) _ f)
  : H ‚ÜíL‚čÜ[‚Ąā] H ‚ÜíL[‚Ąā] ‚Ąā where
  toFun x := {  toFun y := (cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y).integral f
                map_add' := sorry
                map_smul' := sorry
                cont := sorry }
  map_add' := sorry
  map_smul' := sorry
  cont := sorry
```

This defines `toBoundedBilin` as a bounded bilinear functional. The structure is given, but the actual implementation is missing.

```tactics
/-- For each indicator function `Ōá s` of a set `s`, the bounded sesquilinear form
`x, y => ‚ąę f z ‚ąāE_{a, x ,y} z` gives an orthogonal projection `E_{a} s`. Define the map
`s => E_{a} s` as a resolution of identity`.
Probably `s` should be restricted to measurable set (otherwise defined to be `0`) to assure
`not_measurable'`.
cf. Rudin "Functional Analysis" Theorem 12.22, the definition (9) and later.
-/
def toResolutionOfIdentity : ResolutionOfIdentity (spectrum ‚Ąā a) H where
  measureOf' s := InnerProductSpace.continuousLinearMapOfBilin
    (@toBoundedBilin H inst‚úĚ¬≤ inst‚úĚ¬Ļ inst‚úĚ a ha 1 (w.indicator 1))
  isOrthogonalProjection' := sorry
```

This defines `toResolutionOfIdentity` as the resolution of identity corresponding to `a`. The `measureOf'` is defined using `InnerProductSpace.continuousLinearMapOfBilin` and `toBoundedBilin`. The `isOrthogonalProjection'` part is missing.

Now, we need to prove the theorem:
```tactics
theorem riesz_markov_kakutani (a : H ‚ÜíL[‚Ąā] H) (ha : IsSelfAdjoint a) {f : C((spectrum ‚Ąā a), ‚Ąā)}
    (hf : Continuous f) : Continuous (fun x => (cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y).integral f) := by
```

We need to prove that `fun x => (cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y).integral f` is continuous. 

First, note that `cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y` is the complex measure such that for any continuous function `g`, we have `‚ąę g(z) d(cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y)(z) = ‚ü®x, (cfcHom ha.isStarNormal g) y‚ü©_‚Ąā`.

Therefore, the function `x ‚Ü¶ ‚ąę f(z) d(cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y)(z)` is equal to the function `x ‚Ü¶ ‚ü®x, (cfcHom ha.isStarNormal f) y‚ü©_‚Ąā`.

Since the inner product `‚ü®¬∑, ¬∑‚ü©_‚Ąā` is continuous in each variable, the function `x ‚Ü¶ ‚ü®x, (cfcHom ha.isStarNormal f) y‚ü©_‚Ąā` is continuous.

In Lean, we can prove this as follows:

```tactics
import Mathlib
import Mathlib.Analysis.SpecificLimits.Normed
import Mathlib.Analysis.SpecificLimits.Normed.Basic
import Mathlib.Analysis.SpecificLimits.Normed.InnerProductSpace
import Mathlib.Analysis.SpecificLimits.Normed.InnerProductSpace.Basic
import Mathlib.Analysis.SpecificLimits.Normed.InnerProductSpace.Dual
import Mathlib.Analysis.SpecificLimits.Normed.InnerProductSpace.Oriented
import Mathlib.Analysis.SpecificLimits.Normed.InnerProductSpace.Oriented.Basic
import Mathlib.Analysis.SpecificLimits.Normed.InnerProductSpace.Oriented.Dual
import Mathlib.Analysis.SpecificLimits.Normed.InnerProductSpace.Oriented.Basic
import Mathlib.Analysis.SpecificLimits.Normed.InnerProductSpace.Oriented.Dual
```

We're importing the necessary libraries for working with inner product spaces and continuity.

```tactics
/-!
# The Spectral Theorem

-/

@[expose] public section

open InnerProductSpace ContinuousLinearMap ZeroAtInfty ZeroAtInftyContinuousMap MeasureTheory
```

We're opening the necessary namespaces to access inner product space structures, continuous linear maps, and measure theory concepts.

```tactics
noncomputable section

variable {H : Type*} [NormedAddCommGroup H] [InnerProductSpace ‚Ąā H] [CompleteSpace H]
  {a : H ‚ÜíL[‚Ąā] H} (ha : IsSelfAdjoint a)
```

We're defining the variables and assumptions for the theorem.

```tactics
variable (f : C((spectrum ‚Ąā a), ‚Ąā))
```

Now we define the theorem:

```tactics
theorem riesz_markov_kakutani (a : H ‚ÜíL[‚Ąā] H) (ha : IsSelfAdjoint a) {f : C((spectrum ‚Ąā a), ‚Ąā)}
    (hf : Continuous f) : Continuous (fun x => (cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y).integral f) := by
```

We need to show the function `x ‚Ü¶ ‚ąę f(z) d(cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y)(z)` is continuous.

First, we need to relate the integral to the inner product. By the definition of `cfc_toComplexMeasure`, we have that for any continuous function `g`, `‚ąę g(z) d(cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y)(z) = ‚ü®x, (cfcHom ha.isStarNormal g) y‚ü©_‚Ąā`.

Therefore, `fun x => (cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y).integral f` is equal to `fun x => ‚ü®x, (cfcHom ha.isStarNormal f) y‚ü©_‚Ąā`.

The latter function is a linear functional in `x`, and since the inner product is continuous in each variable, this function is continuous.

In Lean, we can prove this as follows:

```tactics
have h1 : (fun x : H => (cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y).integral f) = fun x : H => innerSL ‚Ąā x ((cfcHom ha.isStarNormal f) y) := by
  funext x
  have h2 : (cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y).integral f = innerSL ‚Ąā x ((cfcHom ha.isStarNormal f) y) := by
    have h3 : (cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y) = ComplexRMK.rieszMeasure (compSL C‚āÄ((spectrum ‚Ąā a), ‚Ąā) C((spectrum ‚Ąā a), ‚Ąā) ‚Ąā _ _ (cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y) (@ZeroAtInftyContinuousMap.ContinuousMap.liftZeroAtInftyCLE (spectrum ‚Ąā a) ‚Ąā ‚Ąā _ _ _ _ _ _).symm.toContinuousLinearMap) := rfl
    rw [h3]
    have h4 : ‚ąÄ (g : C((spectrum ‚Ąā a), ‚Ąā)), Continuous g ‚Üí (ComplexRMK.rieszMeasure (compSL C‚āÄ((spectrum ‚Ąā a), ‚Ąā) C((spectrum ‚Ąā a), ‚Ąā) ‚Ąā _ _ (cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y) (@ZeroAtInftyContinuousMap.ContinuousMap.liftZeroAtInftyCLE (spectrum ‚Ąā a) ‚Ąā ‚Ąā _ _ _ _ _ _).symm.toContinuousLinearMap)).integral g = innerSL ‚Ąā x ((cfcHom ha.isStarNormal g) y) := by
      intro g hg
      have h5 : (ComplexRMK.rieszMeasure (compSL C‚āÄ((spectrum ‚Ąā a), ‚Ąā) C((spectrum ‚Ąā a), ‚Ąā) ‚Ąā _ _ (cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y) (@ZeroAtInftyContinuousMap.ContinuousMap.liftZeroAtInftyCLE (spectrum ‚Ąā a) ‚Ąā ‚Ąā _ _ _ _ _ _).symm.toContinuousLinearMap)).integral g = (compSL C‚āÄ((spectrum ‚Ąā a), ‚Ąā) C((spectrum ‚Ąā a), ‚Ąā) ‚Ąā _ _ (cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y) (@ZeroAtInftyContinuousMap.ContinuousMap.liftZeroAtInftyCLE (spectrum ‚Ąā a) ‚Ąā ‚Ąā _ _ _ _ _ _).symm.toContinuousLinearMap).integral g := by
        rfl
      rw [h5]
      simp only [compSL_apply]
      <;> simp [innerSL, cfc_toLinearFunctional_apply, toLinearFunctional_apply, cfcCLM_apply]
      <;> ring
```

Wait, this is getting complicated. Let's try to simplify.

We need to show that `fun x => (cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y).integral f` is equal to `fun x => innerSL ‚Ąā x ((cfcHom ha.isStarNormal f) y)`. 

Let's try to prove this equality directly.

```tactics
funext x
```

Now we need to show that `(cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y).integral f = innerSL ‚Ąā x ((cfcHom ha.isStarNormal f) y)`.

```tactics
have h2 : (cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y).integral f = innerSL ‚Ąā x ((cfcHom ha.isStarNormal f) y) := by
```

To prove this, we need to use the definition of `cfc_toComplexMeasure`. 

`cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y` is defined as `ComplexRMK.rieszMeasure (compSL C‚āÄ((spectrum ‚Ąā a), ‚Ąā) C((spectrum ‚Ąā a), ‚Ąā) ‚Ąā _ _ (cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y) (@ZeroAtInftyContinuousMap.ContinuousMap.liftZeroAtInftyCLE (spectrum ‚Ąā a) ‚Ąā ‚Ąā _ _ _ _ _ _).symm.toContinuousLinearMap)`.

So we need to show that `ComplexRMK.rieszMeasure ... .integral f = innerSL ‚Ąā x ((cfcHom ha.isStarNormal f) y)`.

But by the definition of `ComplexRMK.rieszMeasure`, for a continuous function `g`, we have `ComplexRMK.rieszMeasure L.integral g = L g`, where `L` is the linear functional.

In our case, `L = cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y`. So `L g = innerSL ‚Ąā x ((cfcHom ha.isStarNormal g) y)`.

Therefore, `ComplexRMK.rieszMeasure L.integral g = innerSL ‚Ąā x ((cfcHom ha.isStarNormal g) y)`.

So we need to apply this to our specific `f`.

```tactics
have h3 : (cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y).integral f = (cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y) f := by
  have h4 : (cfc_toComplexMeasure ha x y) = ComplexRMK.rieszMeasure (compSL C‚āÄ((spectrum ‚Ąā a), ‚Ąā) C((spectrum ‚Ąā a), ‚Ąā) ‚Ąā _ _ (cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y) (@ZeroAtInftyContinuousMap.ContinuousMap.liftZeroAtInftyCLE (spectrum ‚Ąā a) ‚Ąā ‚Ąā _ _ _ _ _ _).symm.toContinuousLinearMap) := rfl
  rw [h4]
  have h5 : Continuous (fun (z : (spectrum ‚Ąā a)) => (compSL C‚āÄ((spectrum ‚Ąā a), ‚Ąā) C((spectrum ‚Ąā a), ‚Ąā) ‚Ąā _ _ (cfc_toLinearFunctional ha x y) (@ZeroAtInftyContinuousMap.ContinuousMap.liftZeroAtInftyCLE (spectrum ‚Ąā a) ‚Ąā ‚Ąā _ _ _ _ _ _).symm.toContinuousLinearMap) f z) := by
    simp [compSL_apply]
    all_goals try continuity
```

